## tddmaster orchestrator

State-driven orchestration. Do NOT read `.tddmaster/` files directly — tddmaster provides everything via JSON.

### Protocol

    {{.Command}} start <slug>                         # create and start a new spec
    {{.Command}} next <slug>                          # get or advance the next action
    {{.Command}} next <slug> --answer="response"      # submit an answer and advance

`next <slug>` is the single master-loop command. Call it to receive a JSON `Action` object, act on it, then call it again with `--answer` to submit your response and receive the next action. Everything the agent needs is in the JSON output.

### JSON contract

Every `{{.Command}} next` call returns an `Action` object:

```json
{
  "action": "ask|instruct|notify|terminal|error",
  "instruction": "...",
  "delegateAgent": "tddmaster-executor|tddmaster-planner|tddmaster-test-writer|tddmaster-verifier|tddmaster-auditor",
  "expectedInput": {
    "format": "json|text|flag",
    "submitCmd": "{{.Command}} next <slug> --answer='...'",
    "example": "..."
  },
  "interactiveOptions": [
    { "label": "...", "description": "..." }
  ],
  "commandMap": { "label": "{{.Command}} next <slug> --answer='...'" },
  "multiSelect": false
}
```

In the execution phase, `instruct` actions ALWAYS carry a `tasks` array — even when there is only one ready task. Each entry is a self-contained unit of work:

```json
{
  "action": "instruct",
  "instruction": "orchestration summary...",
  "tasks": [
    {
      "taskId": "task-1",
      "stage": "green",
      "instruction": "...",
      "delegateAgent": "tddmaster-executor",
      "expectedInput": { "format": "json", "submitCmd": "{{.Command}} next <slug> --answer='...'", "example": "..." },
      "worktree": { "path": ".tddmaster/worktrees/<slug>/task-1", "branch": "tddmaster/<slug>/task-1" }
    }
  ]
}
```

Report submits in the execution phase MUST include the `taskId` of the task they belong to.

Drive entirely off the JSON:

- `action: "ask"` — present the question or delegate to `delegateAgent` if set; submit the answer via `--answer`.
- `action: "instruct"` — spawn the `delegateAgent` sub-agent with the `instruction`; submit its status report via `--answer`.
- `action: "notify"` — display to the user; call `next` again (no `--answer` needed).
- `action: "terminal"` — spec is complete or cancelled; stop the loop.
- `action: "error"` — surface the error to the user; do not advance.
- `interactiveOptions` — use AskUserQuestion; resolve selection via `commandMap`.
- `expectedInput.submitCmd` — use this exact command shape to submit.

### Core rules

- Call `{{.Command}} next` ONCE per interaction. One action, one response, one submit.
- Never batch-submit. Never answer discovery questions yourself.
- Never skip steps or infer decisions. Ask first. Explicit > Clever.
- NEVER suggest bypassing or skipping tddmaster. Discovery is not overhead.
- NEVER ask permission to run the next command. Each step has one next step. Just run it.
- Execute tddmaster commands IMMEDIATELY — the JSON output has all context needed.
- Display `roadmap` before content. Display `gate` prominently.

### Important task gate (runtime-delegated)

When `next` returns an `action: "ask"` with `delegateAgent: "tddmaster-planner"`, the engine has detected an important task without an approved plan. The JSON will contain an `importantTaskGate` block. Required behavior:

- The gate action may carry a `tasks` array. The entry with stage `"gate"` is the question itself — do NOT spawn it as a worker. Every other entry is a regular ready task: dispatch them as parallel sub-agents (worktree protocol applies) while the plan gate is being handled; submit their reports as usual.
- Spawn `tddmaster-planner` (read-only: Read/Grep/Glob/LS) with the task scope plus `priorFeedback` when present. Do NOT edit files in this phase.
- Present the planner output to the user in full detail — a single-line summary is NOT acceptable. The presentation must include: the full `approach` narrative, each entry in `touchedFiles` with an explicit reason why that file is touched, each `designPattern` with how it is applied, each `bestPractice`, and every `assumption`. Omitting any of these fields is a protocol violation.
- After presenting the full plan, ask the user via AskUserQuestion with options `accept | revise | reject`.
- Gate submits MUST include the `taskId` of the gated task (take it from the stage `"gate"` entry in `tasks`).
- On accept: submit `{{.Command}} next <slug> --answer='{"taskId":"<taskId>","plan":{...},"accepted":true}'`.
- On revise/reject: submit `{{.Command}} next <slug> --answer='{"taskId":"<taskId>","planFeedback":"<reason>"}'` — gate re-fires with `priorFeedback` populated and `attemptCount` incremented.
- The gate re-appears idempotently after every sibling report submit until its answer is submitted. Spawn the planner and present the plan ONCE; when the same gate re-appears, do NOT re-spawn the planner or re-ask the user — just submit the pending gate answer when it is ready.

Once approved, `touchedFiles` in the plan is binding — if work needs a file outside the list, STOP and report `blocked`.

The gate is configured per spec in the spec-settings step (`importantTaskGateEnabled`).

### Cross-artifact analysis phase (runtime-delegated)

After refinement and before execution, the engine runs a cross-artifact analysis phase that pressure-tests the whole task list for contradictions, gaps, and overlaps. It is always on and is no-op-safe — with 0 tasks or 0 criteria nothing special is needed; the phase simply passes through.

When `next` returns an `action: "instruct"` with `delegateAgent: "tddmaster-auditor"`, spawn `tddmaster-auditor` (read-only) with the `instruction`. The auditor inspects the tasks, their Given/When/Then criteria, edge cases, and any approved plans, then returns JSON:

```json
{"verdict": "clean|issues|block", "findings": [{"severity": "...", "category": "...", "taskId": "...", "acId": "...", "detail": "...", "suggestion": "...", "source": "..."}]}
```

Submit the auditor JSON via `--answer`. The engine merges the auditor findings with precomputed structural linter findings.

- Severity policy is STRICT: only `info`-severity findings are advisory. If every finding is `info` (or there are none), the phase passes through to execution — display the findings and continue.
- If ANY finding has severity other than `info` (e.g. `warn` or `block`), `next` returns an `action: "ask"` whose `interactiveOptions` are `return-to-refinement | accept-anyway | edit`. Display the flagged findings prominently, then ask the user via AskUserQuestion and resolve the selection through `commandMap`:
  - `return-to-refinement` — apply a refinement `payload` inline to address the flagged findings and re-run the audit in place (no phase transition); submit `{{.Command}} next <slug> --answer='{"action":"return-to-refinement","payload":{...}}'`. The `payload` is required — an empty payload leaves the tasks unchanged and the same findings recur.
  - `accept-anyway` — accept the analysis despite the flagged findings and continue; submit `{{.Command}} next <slug> --answer='accept-anyway'`.
  - `edit` — edit the tasks inline (a refine payload) and re-run the audit; submit `{{.Command}} next <slug> --answer='{"action":"edit","payload":{...}}'`.

The re-audit loop is capped; after the attempt limit the phase auto-accepts and continues to execution.

### TDD protocol (runtime-delegated)

When TDD is enabled the engine emits stage-specific `delegateAgent` values in the `instruct` action. Drive off the JSON — do not hardcode the flow:

- `delegateAgent: "tddmaster-test-writer"` and stage `red` — write failing tests ONLY; no implementation code.
- `delegateAgent: "tddmaster-executor"` and stage `green` — implement clean, working code that makes failing tests pass. Submit the executor's status report to `next`. Do NOT spawn the verifier yourself — the engine dispatches `tddmaster-verifier` as a separate stage on the next `next` call.
- `delegateAgent: "tddmaster-executor"` and stage `refactor` — apply every refactor note VERBATIM; behavior must not change and all tests must continue to pass.
- `delegateAgent: "tddmaster-verifier"` — verify the work; submit a pass/fail report.

Include `tddPhase` in status reports. When `tddFailureReport` is present in the instruction, address `failedACs` before reporting done. In parallel execution, stage actions carry a `taskId` and every stage runs inside that task's worktree.

### Parallel execution (worktree protocol)

- For each entry in the `tasks` array, spawn a sub-agent: {{if .ParallelSubagents}}spawn ALL entries as sub-agents in the SAME message so they run in parallel.{{else}}this host does not support parallel sub-agent spawning — run the entries one by one, sequentially; the rest of the protocol is unchanged.{{end}}
- Before spawning a task's sub-agent, create its worktree: `git worktree add <worktree.path> -b <worktree.branch>` (base = current branch HEAD). If the worktree already exists, reuse it (resume). Run `git worktree prune` once at session start.
- ALL stages of a task (red, green, refactor, verify) run in the SAME worktree. The verifier runs read-only in that same worktree. Tests and coverage run inside the worktree.
- Each sub-agent instruction includes the engine-provided `worktree` block verbatim. Sub-agents NEVER call the {{.Command}} CLI — submitting is exclusively the orchestrator's job, and submits are serialized.
- MERGE-THEN-SUBMIT (binding): BEFORE submitting a task's terminal (done) report, commit in the worktree → `git merge --no-ff <worktree.branch>` on the main working branch → `git worktree remove <worktree.path>` → `git branch -d <worktree.branch>` → THEN submit the report. This guarantees dependent tasks open their worktrees from an up-to-date base.
- Merge conflict: the orchestrator resolves it. If it cannot, run `git merge --abort`, leave the worktree in place, and submit `{"taskId":"...","blocked":["merge-conflict: <files>"],...}`.
- UNBLOCK: a blocked task stays out of the ready set until a new report clears it. Once the obstacle is resolved (e.g. the user fixed the conflict), submit a report for that `taskId` with no `blocked` entries. A bare report (only `taskId`) just clears the flag and the flow resumes from the stage where the task stopped; a report carrying real stage results (e.g. the completed done report held back by a merge conflict) is processed as that stage's result — do not re-run work that already finished.
- NO-GIT FALLBACK: before processing a batch, run `git rev-parse --is-inside-work-tree`. If the project is not a git repo, skip all worktree steps and run the batch tasks SEQUENTIALLY in the project root (no isolation for concurrent writes); DAG, `taskId`, and submit rules apply unchanged.
- On a deadlock/all-blocked `error` action, stop the loop, display the blocked and waiting tasks as a table, and ask the user. After the user resolves an obstacle, use the UNBLOCK report above — do NOT enter a retry loop.
- Spawn sub-agents only for tasks whose report has not yet been submitted — the engine idempotently re-lists a task that is still running.

### Refinement

During the refinement phase, adjust the task list with a dedicated upsert command that does NOT advance the phase:

    {{.Command}} refine <slug> --answer='{...}'

Before setting per-task `tddEnabled` or `important` flags, ask the USER via AskUserQuestion; then include the confirmed values in the refinement JSON. Example payload:

```json
{
  "update": {"task-1": {"criteria": [{"given": "a logged-out user", "when": "they submit valid credentials", "then": "a session is created"}], "tddEnabled": true, "important": false, "edgeCases": ["empty input", "concurrent access"], "dependsOn": []}},
  "add":    [{"title": "New task", "criteria": [{"given": "an empty cart", "when": "checkout is requested", "then": "the request is rejected"}], "tddEnabled": false, "edgeCases": ["nil pointer", "max length exceeded"], "dependsOn": ["task-1"]}],
  "remove": ["task-3"]
}
```

Each criterion is a Given/When/Then triple (`given`/`when`/`then`); `then` is required, `given` and `when` are optional.

`dependsOn` is a list of task IDs that must be `done` before the task becomes ready; tasks without dependencies run in parallel during execution. Self-dependencies, unknown IDs, and cycles are rejected. Removing a task that others depend on is rejected — update the dependents' `dependsOn` in the same payload.

When satisfied with the task list, advance with:

    {{.Command}} next <slug> --answer="approve"

Note: `refine` is only valid in the refinement phase.

### Spec lifecycle commands (out of band)

Manage a spec outside the phase machine. These act on `.tddmaster/specs/<slug>/` artifacts only — never user code or tests.

    {{.Command}} list [--archived]        # show specs with phase + status (or archived ones)
    {{.Command}} rollback <slug> <phase>  # pull a spec back to an earlier phase (resets that phase + all after it)
    {{.Command}} archive <slug>           # move spec to .tddmaster/archive/<slug>
    {{.Command}} restore <slug>           # move an archived spec back to active
    {{.Command}} cancel <slug> [--force]  # permanently delete a spec (typed-slug confirm in a TTY; --force to skip)

- `rollback` targets a canonical phase ID (`spec-settings`, `discovery`, `spec-proposal`, `refinement`, `cross-artifact-analysis`, `execution`, `rule-learning`); forward rollback is rejected and global rule files are preserved (a warning is printed). After it, `next` resumes normally from the target phase.
- `restore` errors on an active-slug collision. `start` refuses a slug that exists in the archive — run `restore` first or pick another slug. `cancel` without `--force` in a non-interactive shell refuses rather than deleting unconfirmed.

### Spec settings (runs before discovery)

The FIRST `next` action for a new spec is the spec-settings step — an `action: "ask"` with `multiSelect: true` and five settings in `interactiveOptions` (TDD, skip verifier, important task gate, min test coverage, rule learning). Ask the user via AskUserQuestion (multiSelect); never decide settings yourself. Aggregate the selections and submit ALL five as a JSON object, e.g. `{{.Command}} next <slug> --answer='{"tddEnabled":true,"skipVerifierEnabled":false,"importantTaskGateEnabled":false,"minTestCoverage":80,"ruleLearningEnabled":false}'`. A selected toggle means `true`; unselected means `false`. `minTestCoverage` is a number (default 80; set to 0 to disable). `ruleLearningEnabled` defaults to `false`. After submit, discovery begins automatically.

### Rule learning phase

The rule learning phase runs after execution completes, but only when `ruleLearningEnabled` is on. If no learnings emerge the phase is a no-op.

When the engine emits `action: "instruct"` with `delegateAgent: "tddmaster-rule-synthesizer"`, spawn the synthesizer to PROPOSE rules as a JSON array:

```json
{"rules": [{"scope": "executor", "name": "no-globals", "content": "Never use global variables.", "rationale": "..."}]}
```

Present the proposed rules to the user and ask via AskUserQuestion with options `accept | revise | reject`:

- **accept** — the synthesizer APPLIES the rules via the non-interactive CLI (one call per rule):
  `{{.Command}} rule add --scope <scope> --name <name> --content-file <path>`
  The synthesizer writes content to a temp file first, then calls the command. It never edits `.tddmaster/rules/` directly and never passes `--overwrite`.
- **revise** — re-propose with the user's feedback; submit `--answer='{"feedback":"<reason>"}'`
- **reject** — no rules written; submit `--answer='{"accepted":false}'`

### Discovery flow

The discovery phase runs as a single sequence of steps delivered via `next` JSON: listen-first → mode selection → premise challenge → 7 questions → synthesis (approve). Drive each step entirely off the returned `Action`; submit each answer with `{{.Command}} next <slug> --answer=...`. Do not jump ahead or collapse steps.

Ask EVERY discovery question via the AskUserQuestion tool — never as plain prose or a "write your answer, I'll submit" prompt. For each of the 7 questions, propose 2-4 concrete candidate answers as options (your best inferences from the spec description, listen-first context, and selected mode); the user picks one or writes their own. The question instruction in the `Action` JSON spells this out.

### Interactive choices

- Use AskUserQuestion for `interactiveOptions`. Use `commandMap` to resolve selections.
- Listen-first step (mode not yet chosen, no user context): ask the single open-ended context question via AskUserQuestion with a free-form prompt. Do NOT fabricate options.
- Premise challenge step: ask each premise via a separate AskUserQuestion call (agree / disagree / revise with free-form notes). Aggregate the answers client-side, then submit the final JSON payload.

### Stop / resume

When `next` returns `action: "notify"` and the payload includes `RestartRecommended: true`, the iteration limit for this session has been reached. Either start a new conversation and call `{{.Command}} next <slug>` to resume, or submit `{{.Command}} next <slug> --answer="continue"` in the current conversation to reset the counter and keep going.

### Git

Read-only: log, diff, status, show, blame. No write commands (commit, push, checkout, etc.). NARROW EXCEPTION — worktree lifecycle only: `git worktree add/remove/prune/list`, `git add`/`git commit` inside a task worktree, `git merge` on the main working branch, `git branch -d`. `push`, `rebase`, and `reset --hard` remain forbidden.

### Execution

- Re-read files before and after editing. Files >500 LOC: read in chunks.
- Run type-check + lint after every edit. Never mark AC passed if type-check fails.
- If search returns few results, re-run narrower — assume truncation.
- Clean dead code before structural refactors on files >300 LOC.
- Complete the spec — no mid-execution pauses or checkpoints.
- `meta` block has resume context for session start or after compaction.
